 German Kurt, Heinz, Otto, Achim, Dieter, Erwin, Hans, Helmut, Reinhold, Erna, Florian, Fritz.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for an embittered or cantankerous person, from Middle High German <i>sūr</i>, German <i>sauer</i> ‘sour’. In Jewish families, it is mainly artificial, assigned at random by Austrian clerks. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Denmark, Poland, Czechia, Croatia, and Slovenia.","Czech and Slovenian (<b>Šauer</b>): from German   Schauer  . In Slovenia, it is in part of Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) origin."]}]},{"name":"Aronde","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jeanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jeanne De Gournay Sur Aronde was born in 1232, in Gournay-sur-Aronde, Oise, Picardie, France, her father, Henri De Gournay Sur Aronde, was 26 and her mother, Dame Marie de Conty de Frémontiers, was 24. She had at least 1 daughter with Jean De Poissy. She died in 1278, in Poissy, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1232–1278":"1232–1278","1208–1250":"1208–1250","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1206–1257":"1206–1257","1209–1232":"1209–1232","1206":"1206","1257":"1257","après 1232":"pärast 1232","1278":"1278","1232":"1232","1250":"1250","vers 1225":"umbes 1225","1293":"1293","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Gournay-sur-Aronde, Oise, Picardie, France":"Gournay-sur-Aronde, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Abbecourt, Oise, Picardie, France":"Abbecourt, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Poissy, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Poissy, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1232–1278":"1232–1278","1208–1250":"1208–1250","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1206–1257":"1206–1257","1209–1232":"1209–1232","1206":"1206","1257":"1257","après 1232":"1232 jälkeen","1278":"1278","1232":"1232","1250":"1250","vers 1225":"noin 1225","1293":"1293","1209":"1209","1208":"1208","Gournay-sur-Aronde, Oise, Picardie, France":"Gournay-sur-Aronde, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","Abbecourt, Oise, Picardie, France":"Abbecourt, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","Poissy, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Poissy, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"1232–1278":"1232–1278","1208–1250":"1208–1250","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1206–1257":"1206–1257","1209–1232":"1209–1232","1206":"1206","1257":"1257","après 1232":"après 1232","1278":"1278","1232":"1232","1250":"1250",